Happy December!! Trying to give you guys the best possible gift by letting you pick any design you want for just a penny. 🎁

I am asking a favor of you guys to limit the number to just three quilts sent in for this month though.❤️

When I did this sale last May in place of my normal one design, it was crazy how many quilts we got! I was blown away to say the least. In a good way, and in an “Oh sh** what have I done!” way too!😁 

I want to treat my subscribers for sure, and I don’t want the turnaround time to get out of control either.  I appreciate you all so much!! Thank you!!

Please feel free to message me any time if you have questions.🤗

Hello December and Happy Monday!!✨ 

So I traditionally take this month off on the long arm penny special to enjoy the season as best as I can, and I’m sticking to it this year too, kind of.😉 

Last month, I started offering something new called the Penny Savers Club through the Instagram subscriptions.  It’s $4.99 a month to join, and you get the option of 3 MORE penny designs each month over just the normal 1 that gets offered. I’ve opened up a few posts from my subscription page so you can preview what your designs would be for this month and what they were for last month. It might be worth checking out, just saying.😉 The preview posts will be back private and only for Penny Saver Club members to see after the end of the month. 

Seriously though, I appreciate each and every one of you guys so much!! “You’re so money and you don’t even know it!” We just watched this movie over the weekend. Do you know it?😆

Let’s make a Layer Cake circle skirt!! This video took longer to edit together than to sew the whole skirt I think.😆

First off, you should watch @made_everyday YouTube video on how to make a circle skirt. I’m definitely a quilter first, so sewing clothes is new for me. Her videos are great! My instructions are very basic, but you can totally make this skirt. Here we go!

Supplies: 
1 Layer Cake
1.5”-3” wide Elastic (mine is 1.5” on this skirt)

1. Piece your layer cake squares into a 6 x 6 patchwork panel. 
2. Fold your “quilt” top into fourths and cut your waist radius measurement out of the folded corner. Use the formula below to calculate your radius. 
Waist measurement + 2” / 6.28 = radius measurement 
3. Cut your elastic to your exact waist measurement and sew the ends together with a 1/2” seam allowance. Place pins equally around your waistband. Use the seam and fold it in half to find where to mark your pins. 
4. Pin your waistband RST with your skirt. Match up the 4 pins with the 4 seams in the top of the patchwork skirt. 
5. Sew your waistband to your skirt with a 1/4” seam allowance. Make sure to backstitch at the beginning and end and to stretch the elastic as you go around. 
6. Topstitch around the bottom hem of your skirt with a 1/4” seam allowance and you’re done!
